4
00:00:10.273 --> 00:00:12.459
Be it music, drawing, sewing, woodwork

5
00:00:12.459 --> 00:00:13.893
poetry or anything at all.

6
00:00:13.942 --> 00:00:17.349
Some people, like Chris Spheeris make a life of creating.

7
00:00:17.675 --> 00:00:20.117
Aside from selling more than a million CD's

8
00:00:20.117 --> 00:00:21.946
and winning awards for his music,

9
00:00:22.091 --> 00:00:24.210
Chris creates something new everyday.

10
00:00:24.355 --> 00:00:26.584
From photography, gardening and poetry.

11
00:00:26.584 --> 00:00:30.290
To fixing old clocks, Chris says, "we were born to create."

12
00:00:30.324 --> 00:00:35.324 line:15% 
(soft instrumental music)

13
00:00:38.249 --> 00:00:40.873
You are the most creative person I've ever met

14
00:00:40.873 --> 00:00:43.241
personally in my lifetime and the reason is

15
00:00:43.241 --> 00:00:45.491
not only because you've had an incredible

16
00:00:45.491 --> 00:00:47.720
career in music, but also this

17
00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:50.221
extends to everything you do in life.

18
00:00:50.323 --> 00:00:53.171
Photography, renovation of homes.

19
00:00:53.171 --> 00:00:55.197
You're like this incredible artistic

20
00:00:55.197 --> 00:00:57.704
designer for architectural forms.

21
00:00:57.704 --> 00:01:00.189
There's nothing you touch that doesn't turn

22
00:01:00.189 --> 00:01:01.943
into something really beautiful.

23
00:01:02.397 --> 00:01:04.317
And I'm not just saying that to compliment you.

24
00:01:04.317 --> 00:01:07.666
I'm laying the foundation for a conversation

25
00:01:07.666 --> 00:01:10.727
about creativity and why this is not what's

26
00:01:10.727 --> 00:01:12.556
happening in most of our lives.

27
00:01:12.818 --> 00:01:15.083
It's just not happening in most of our lives.

28
00:01:15.121 --> 00:01:17.340
So let's start with when you're a little kid.

29
00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:19.499
I always like to start at the beginning.

30
00:01:19.782 --> 00:01:22.108
What was going on in your life that you

31
00:01:22.108 --> 00:01:23.979
started sensing you had to create.

32
00:01:25.073 --> 00:01:27.771
<v ->I think, right away I'm thinking of the imprint.</v>

33
00:01:27.771 --> 00:01:31.184
What that means to me is, I was imprinted to feel boundless.

34
00:01:32.934 --> 00:01:36.010
I wasn't spoiled, not in that sense, not materially.

35
00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:40.721
But I was imprinted to feel like I could create anything.

36
00:01:41.511 --> 00:01:43.198
Play was always encouraged.

37
00:01:43.198 --> 00:01:44.883
Anything that had to do with the

38
00:01:44.883 --> 00:01:47.624
mind or with art, with music.

39
00:01:47.624 --> 00:01:50.365
Any of that as a child was always nourished,

40
00:01:50.365 --> 00:01:52.573
encouraged, and never judged.

41
00:01:52.573 --> 00:01:54.312
That was a big thing, you know judgement

42
00:01:54.312 --> 00:01:56.612
is gonna be a theme I think in this conversation

43
00:01:56.612 --> 00:01:58.702
because creativity and judgement,

44
00:01:58.702 --> 00:02:01.523
they work against each other completely.

45
00:02:01.764 --> 00:02:03.022
Judgement's sort of the antithesis

46
00:02:03.022 --> 00:02:04.707
