00:13:01.209 --> 00:13:03.630
philosophies believe that I did ask to come here.

310
00:13:03.630 --> 00:13:07.299
My philosophy is that, I woke up one day

311
00:13:07.299 --> 00:13:08.781
and looked around and said, "Oh I'm here."

312
00:13:08.781 --> 00:13:13.080
And I spent five decades trying to figure out why.

313
00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:15.448
And then I finally realized, you know,

314
00:13:15.448 --> 00:13:18.135
I don't have a clue and I'm a pretty smart guy.

315
00:13:18.135 --> 00:13:20.994
So I'm gonna let that all go and I'm going to

316
00:13:20.994 --> 00:13:24.151
allow the process of me to happen.

317
00:13:24.151 --> 00:13:27.799
So I'm a lot more of an observer now in terms

318
00:13:27.799 --> 00:13:30.817
of this funny and unpredictable process

319
00:13:30.817 --> 00:13:33.814
that happens through my vehicle, okay.

320
00:13:33.814 --> 00:13:35.596
So the reason I'm bringing all this up is

321
00:13:35.596 --> 00:13:37.270
because I am talking about creativity

322
00:13:37.270 --> 00:13:38.433
when I'm mentioning all of this.

323
00:13:38.433 --> 00:13:42.241
Because creativity is not some coveted secret

324
00:13:42.241 --> 00:13:43.883
that only artists have access to.

325
00:13:43.883 --> 00:13:45.654
And a lot of people believe that.

326
00:13:45.654 --> 00:13:47.883
They believe that, "I'm not creative."

327
00:13:47.883 --> 00:13:49.789
When someone looks at me and says they're not creative,

328
00:13:49.789 --> 00:13:51.272
I look at them and I go, "I don't think you

329
00:13:51.272 --> 00:13:52.893
"understand what creativity is."

330
00:13:52.893 --> 00:13:55.175
<v Voiceover>And so how do you describe to them what it is?</v>

331
00:13:55.175 --> 00:13:57.010
From your perspective?

332
00:13:57.010 --> 00:13:59.261
<v ->I say, "Do you cook, do you do the laundry?</v>

333
00:13:59.261 --> 00:14:01.136
"Do you wake up in the morning and get dressed?

334
00:14:01.136 --> 00:14:02.235
I say, "You're being creative all

